        "text": "The document discusses the issue of inefficient pricing and dispatch due to frequent Out-of-Market (OOM) actions to manage congestion in Long Island's 69 kV facilities. It recommends that the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) model these transmission constraints for better pricing and management.\n\nThe section focuses on \"Guarantee Payment Uplift Charges,\" which are payments made by NYISO to market participants that are not covered by Locational Based Marginal Pricing (LBMP) and other revenues. These charges are difficult to hedge and obscure economic signals, so minimizing them is crucial. The document highlights that when markets reflect reliability requirements, uplift charges should be low.\n\nIn 2018, the guarantee payment uplift totaled $77 million, a 102% increase from 2017, mainly due to increased supplemental commitments, OOM dispatch, and higher natural gas prices. New York City saw the most significant increase, with $45 million in charges, a 119% rise from 2017. Over $26 million was paid for N-1-1 local requirements. The document suggests that modeling local reserve requirements for N-1-1 needs could reduce these charges and improve price transparency.",
