        "score": 0.5354522,
        "text": "The document discusses the process and results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) study cycle related to deliverability and transmission planning for energy projects. It outlines the requirements for projects to pay for upgrades to receive Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) and Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) rights. The study identifies necessary upgrades to ensure projects can deliver energy without violating transmission constraints.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The Class Year Study helps developers decide whether to pay for required upgrades, receive ERIS or CRIS rights, or withdraw.\n- Recent studies have taken about two years, with increasing numbers of participants and costs.\n- CY21 began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS.\n- The CY21 SUF Study identified over $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability.\n- Sixteen projects requesting 4 GW of CRIS were not fully deliverable, with less than 400 MW partially deliverable.\n- NYISO identified $1.5 billion in System Deliverability Upgrades (SDUs) for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP.\n- The document includes a table summarizing the results and costs of the CY21 SDU Study.",
