        "score": 0.5156092,
        "text": "The document page discusses the gross profitability and quantity of scheduled real-time external transactions between PJM and NE primary interfaces from 2018 to 2022. It includes a bar graph showing the 5-year average profit and scheduled megawatts (MW) for imports and exports between NY/NE and NY/PJM.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Recommendation to Reduce Charges**: The document suggests eliminating or reducing charges at PJM interfaces to improve efficiency and integration of renewable resources. High fees can lead to curtailment of renewable generation as it cannot be delivered to consumers.\n\n2. **Transmission Charges**: It argues against assigning the same transmission charges to price-sensitive exports as to network load customers, as these charges are meant to cover the cost of the transmission system.\n\n3. **Export Fees**: In 2022, NYISO collected approximately $2.4 million in export fees from real-time exports to PJM, while PJM collected $2.9 million from exports to NYISO. Lower export fees could potentially increase overall fee collection by making CTS transactions more profitable under various conditions.",
